subSubSection.paragraph:
In an investigation of phylogenetic relationships of the groups in question 

Santana (
2008
)

found four unambiguous synapomorphies that indicate the monophyly of the 
Inachoididae
: 
1
) thoracic pleurites V–VIII gymnopleura (see also 

Drach & Guinot, 
1982

; 

1983

; Guinot & Richer de 

Forges, 
1997

); 
2
) female abdominal segments 
5, 6
fused with each other and with telson; 
3
) second antennal segment with a longitudinal carina parallel to the lateral margin of the antennular fossa; and 
4
) female sterno-abdominal cavity deeply concave. The genus 

Inachoides

is also monophyletic as evidenced by the following synapomorphies: 
1
) single rostral spine; 
2
) antennular septum with no lobe or spine and restricted to antennular fossa; 
2
) propod of cheliped strongly swollen; 
4
) ventromesial margin of antennal article 
2
with a low carina; 
5
) ventrolateral margin of subhepathic region with no spine or prominent tubercles. Comparisons of 
P. m e l o i
with representatives of the valid species of 

Inachoides

revealed that 
P. m e l o i
has all the synapomorphies of 
Inachoididae
and 

Inachoides

. Therefore, these synapomorphies support the placement of 
P. m e l o i
in 

Inachoides

.
